  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which countries have a negative population growth and why?",
  "response": "As of the most recent data available, several countries are experiencing negative population growth. This means that the number of deaths exceeds the number of births or immigration levels are not high enough to offset the population decline. Here are some countries with negative population growth and the reasons behind it:\n\n1. **Japan**: Japan has one of the highest life expectancies but one of the lowest birth rates in the world. Social factors such as economic pressures, a growing preference for smaller families, and fewer marriages contribute to the low birth rate. Additionally, Japan has strict immigration policies, further affecting population growth.\n\n2. **Italy**: Italy faces a declining population due to low birth rates and an aging population. Economic uncertainty and changing social norms have led many Italians to delay or forgo having children. Additionally, emigration of young people seeking better opportunities abroad contributes to the population decline.\n\n3. **Germany**: Germany has experienced population decline due to low birth rates and an aging population. Although immigration has helped mitigate the decline, it has not entirely offset the negative growth.\n\n4. **Russia**: Russia has experienced negative population growth due to a combination of high mortality rates, low birth rates, and emigration. Economic difficulties, health issues, and low life expectancy have contributed to the decline.\n\n5. **Ukraine**: The instability created by ongoing conflict, economic challenges, and a declining birth rate have led to negative population growth. Emigration is also a significant factor as many Ukrainians seek better living conditions elsewhere.\n\n6. **Greece**: The economic crisis that began in the late 2000s led to fewer births and higher emigration rates among the younger population, contributing to negative population growth.\n\n7. **Bulgaria**: Bulgaria has one of the highest rates of population decline in the European Union. Factors include low birth rates, high death rates, and significant emigration due to economic challenges.\n\n8. **Portugal**: Like many other European countries, Portugal faces population decline due to low birth rates, an aging population, and emigration of younger people seeking better job opportunities.\n\nThe reasons for negative population growth in these countries are multifaceted and include socio-economic factors, cultural shifts, health issues, and migration patterns. Addressing these trends often requires comprehensive policies aimed at improving economic conditions, healthcare, family support, and immigration.",
